236
00:16:03,514 --> 00:16:05,475
because this model is still aiming

237
00:16:05,535 --> 00:16:07,937
for simplicity and liability.

238
00:16:07,957 --> 00:16:11,659
And next, there's the impact of framing this

239
00:16:11,719 --> 00:16:13,100
as attraction, not affection.

240
00:16:13,420 --> 00:16:15,962
For one, it avoids that conflating platonic warmth

241
00:16:16,022 --> 00:16:18,243
with sexy romantic warmth, but it's

242
00:16:18,323 --> 00:16:21,925
holistic to allow to that broad range of types of interest.

243
00:16:22,306 --> 00:16:24,247
And most importantly, framing it as attraction

244
00:16:24,367 --> 00:16:27,649
better connects it to the NPC's specific active desires,

245
00:16:27,749 --> 00:16:29,070
not reactive gratitude.

246
00:16:30,005 --> 00:16:32,267
As such, the threshold has more weight and meaning.

247
00:16:32,627 --> 00:16:36,430
It means the NPC's attraction has built to a point where they have to act

248
00:16:36,770 --> 00:16:38,451
because their feelings were too strong to ignore.

249
00:16:38,931 --> 00:16:41,393
They choose to act because they embrace their feelings,

250
00:16:41,993 --> 00:16:45,976
or they're compelled to act because they've just been overwhelmed by their feelings.

251
00:16:47,597 --> 00:16:51,459
In terms of a hypothetical example, let's look at how this could work in a game like Dragon Age 2.

252
00:16:51,960 --> 00:16:56,783
In the actual game, the dialogue system lets you shape Hawk's personality outside of romance

253
00:16:57,123 --> 00:16:58,624
towards three personality types.

254
00:16:58,958 --> 00:17:01,499
If you go one step further, though, those personalities

255
00:17:01,519 --> 00:17:04,080
could slot in nicely with certain love interests

256
00:17:04,180 --> 00:17:06,301
and what they might be drawn to in a partner.

257
00:17:06,841 --> 00:17:09,602
And then their romance scenes take on more context.

258
00:17:09,942 --> 00:17:11,923
They visit you that evening because they're

259
00:17:11,963 --> 00:17:15,104
moved, amused, or inflamed by who you are,

260
00:17:15,385 --> 00:17:17,545
not just when you're with them, but all the time.

261
00:17:17,565 --> 00:17:21,807
A model like this can be easily converted to a chemistry card

262
00:17:21,847 --> 00:17:24,488
tower that runs in every moment in dialogue choice,

263
00:17:24,608 --> 00:17:26,149
not only romance set pieces.

264
00:17:27,135 --> 00:17:30,456
So same loop, subtle differences, big impact.

265
00:17:30,856 --> 00:17:32,217
Most of the strengths of kindness coins,

266
00:17:32,557 --> 00:17:33,958
arguably not the weaknesses.

267
00:17:34,158 --> 00:17:37,199
And yes, you are still choosing the right options

268
00:17:37,259 --> 00:17:38,599
to get with a digital hottie,

269
00:17:38,679 --> 00:17:40,200
but the options are more interesting,

270
00:17:40,540 --> 00:17:41,761
the getting with is more organic,

271
00:17:42,061 --> 00:17:43,181
and the story has more depth.

272
00:17:43,922 --> 00:17:45,422
If kindness coins are about saying

273
00:17:45,462 --> 00:17:46,663
and doing the right thing

274
00:17:46,803 --> 00:17:48,624
until you're rewarded with love and sex,

275
00:17:49,104 --> 00:17:51,245
then Chemistry Card Tower is about being

276
00:17:51,285 --> 00:17:54,366
the right kind of person to make the NPC feel that way.

277
00:17:54,974 --> 00:17:59,637
That's what I mean by better wish fulfillment, giving the players a clear, easy path to romantic

278
00:17:59,677 --> 00:18:03,459
and sexual arcs they want, but making that path more meaningful and more interesting,

279
00:18:03,819 --> 00:18:08,901
both to take and to write. In terms of good places to use the chemistry card tower,

280
00:18:08,921 --> 00:18:14,144
one is obviously game genres like RPGs and visual novels that already use kindness coins heavily.

281
00:18:14,304 --> 00:18:18,526
There's no need to design entirely new systems and reinvent the wheel. You can iterate on the

282
00:18:18,586 --> 00:18:22,508
one that's already there, which makes your producers and the people with money very, very happy.

283
00:18:23,868 --> 00:18:27,772
Romantic and sexual narratives with themes of matching, compatibility, and certainty,

284
00:18:27,932 --> 00:18:33,056
because part of the appeal is that you know where things are going to end up when you pick that option.

285
00:18:33,977 --> 00:18:37,040
And for players that are seeking more idealized experiences and stories,

286
00:18:37,060 --> 00:18:39,502
or at least ones that are easy to engage with.

287
00:18:40,123 --> 00:18:41,044
Okay, great.

288
00:18:42,009 --> 00:18:43,469
What if none of those apply?

289
00:18:43,809 --> 00:18:49,671
What if your target player base wants the complication and weirdness and pain of real-world sex and romance?

290
00:18:49,991 --> 00:18:51,831
What if they want it to be hard?

291
00:18:52,171 --> 00:18:53,312
Or maybe you want that.

292
00:18:53,492 --> 00:18:57,773
Maybe you're making a game where the tone or themes don't lend themselves to stories

293
00:18:58,013 --> 00:19:00,593
where love always wins or where you always know what to do.

294
00:19:01,053 --> 00:19:04,394
You may want to tell more realistic stories about confusion, uncertainty.

295
00:19:04,750 --> 00:19:07,471
the random chance that love punches your players in the face.

296
00:19:08,071 --> 00:19:10,892
Because, you know, let's face it, at least when they start,

297
00:19:11,212 --> 00:19:14,712
like, love and sex can involve uncertainty and luck.

298
00:19:15,093 --> 00:19:19,133
Some of it is just the situational luck of meeting the right person at the right time

299
00:19:19,554 --> 00:19:23,134
or experiencing a random moment together that you can't plan for.

300
00:19:23,714 --> 00:19:27,635
And to be honest, in reality, you can't really plan for attraction either.

301
00:19:28,058 --> 00:19:29,998
The spark is tough to predict.

302
00:19:30,399 --> 00:19:32,599
Even when you have a type, it's no guarantee

303
00:19:32,679 --> 00:19:34,780
if you meet that type that you'll actually dig them.

304
00:19:35,600 --> 00:19:38,801
Plus, people don't come with walkthroughs in UI.

305
00:19:39,001 --> 00:19:40,402
You don't know what's going on in their head.

306
00:19:40,422 --> 00:19:41,702
If you're like me, you barely know

307
00:19:41,722 --> 00:19:42,823
what's going on in your head.

308
00:19:43,243 --> 00:19:44,703
None of us know what the hell we're doing.

309
00:19:44,943 --> 00:19:47,644
Luck, it's a goddamn miracle anybody ever manages

310
00:19:47,664 --> 00:19:48,644
to hook up with anyone.

311
00:19:49,465 --> 00:19:51,385
And yet, we risk it anyway.

312
00:19:51,785 --> 00:19:53,686
We take the plunge into mysterious waters

313
00:19:53,726 --> 00:19:56,467
because the love or booty we're looking for is worth it.

314
00:19:57,007 --> 00:19:57,527
And you know what?

315
00:19:58,177 --> 00:20:00,659
That all sounds like great fodder for storytelling.

316
00:20:00,959 --> 00:20:02,880
And it just so happens we're telling stories

317
00:20:03,040 --> 00:20:05,062
in a medium where luck and random chance

318
00:20:05,162 --> 00:20:06,383
are baked into the foundation.

319
00:20:07,164 --> 00:20:10,086
Hence, the second model, the chemistry casino.

320
00:20:10,707 --> 00:20:13,669
As the name suggests, this model incorporates chemistry

321
00:20:13,689 --> 00:20:16,051
and attraction, but adds unpredictability

322
00:20:16,151 --> 00:20:18,873
through game systems like RNG, through the writing,

323
00:20:19,293 --> 00:20:21,695
and through hiding information and feedback.

324
00:20:22,885 --> 00:20:27,008
In the Chemistry Card Tower, you know what the NPC finds attractive.

325
00:20:27,068 --> 00:20:28,569
You know they'll become attracted.

326
00:20:28,829 --> 00:20:30,690
You know they're going to act on it eventually.

327
00:20:31,070 --> 00:20:35,653
In Chemistry Casino, you might not know any of these things for sure

328
00:20:35,753 --> 00:20:38,936
because they're hidden from you or because they're genuinely random.

329
00:20:39,556 --> 00:20:42,818
Now, this still encourages role playing and exploring attraction,

330
00:20:42,998 --> 00:20:46,661
but from a different angle, one that doesn't offer guarantees.

331
00:20:47,286 --> 00:20:54,553
So for example, the NPC's type might not be clearly communicated, meaning you can't just pick an obvious trait that they dig.

332
00:20:54,953 --> 00:20:58,797
You have to feel things out in the moment based on what you think you know about them.

333
00:20:59,217 --> 00:20:59,818
Are you right?

334
00:20:59,838 --> 00:21:03,061
You might never know for sure, but all you can do is try.

335
00:21:03,081 --> 00:21:08,246
And also, being someone's type doesn't always translate into automatic attraction.

336
00:21:08,696 --> 00:21:12,578
It helps and is makes more likely, but it may not be guaranteed.

337
00:21:13,219 --> 00:21:17,001
A good way to look at it, using dice from something other than the casino,

338
00:21:17,281 --> 00:21:23,145
is your character's attractive traits in this may be more like modifiers on a dice roll in D&D,

339
00:21:23,505 --> 00:21:27,727
not a seduction roll, but a roll to see if there's a spark there.

340
00:21:28,608 --> 00:21:31,509
If you have a lot of traits they're drawn to, it's more likely,

341
00:21:31,850 --> 00:21:33,891
but it still might not turn out that way in the end.

342
00:21:34,438 --> 00:21:36,419
And of course, this works in reverse, too.

343
00:21:36,559 --> 00:21:38,741
You might be the opposite of who they usually like,

344
00:21:38,781 --> 00:21:40,802
but boy, for some reason, they're

345
00:21:40,902 --> 00:21:42,043
just feeling it with you.

346
00:21:43,952 --> 00:21:46,514
So actual randomization in chemistry casino design,

347
00:21:46,554 --> 00:21:49,417
so using things like randomized characters, events, RNG,

348
00:21:49,737 --> 00:21:52,820
this is great for games with that game design

349
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:54,541
and narrative design already in place.

350
00:21:55,041 --> 00:21:56,403
For example, Crusader Kings III,

351
00:21:56,923 --> 00:21:58,644
basically a soap opera generator,

352
00:21:58,724 --> 00:22:01,026
thanks to its random characters and events,

353
00:22:01,387 --> 00:22:03,548
marriages, adultery, pregnancies, you name it.

354
00:22:04,009 --> 00:22:06,491
This makes for great emergent storytelling

355
00:22:06,631 --> 00:22:07,512
around love and sex.

356
00:22:08,407 --> 00:22:11,851
But for more traditional game stories, it can be a bit trickier.

357
00:22:12,271 --> 00:22:16,715
So for one thing, for players, most do not want to be blocked from romantic and sexual content

358
00:22:16,956 --> 00:22:21,420
by one stroke of bad luck, particularly if they've been playing for hundreds of hours.

359
00:22:22,020 --> 00:22:22,761
And for writers...

360
00:22:23,462 --> 00:22:28,383
Let's face it, effective romantic and sexual storytelling can often depend on very non-random

361
00:22:28,443 --> 00:22:34,905
things like characterization, pacing, logic. So having random things just happen out of nowhere

362
00:22:34,945 --> 00:22:38,566
with no narrative connecting tissue is going to wreck the whole story, potentially.

363
00:22:39,666 --> 00:22:44,088
If you want randomization and traditional narrative, try a hybrid model. Either have

364
00:22:44,108 --> 00:22:50,010
the narrative be modular and easy to shift around, or have the randomization be light

365
00:22:50,410 --> 00:22:51,970
and subordinate to the narrative.

366
00:22:53,232 --> 00:22:57,633
A good example of this can be found in Monster Prom, where the goal is to ask a monster out to prom.

367
00:22:58,013 --> 00:23:02,454
There is a chemistry system where their attraction is based on whether you have high stats in the

368
00:23:02,514 --> 00:23:08,255
traits they like, but the scenes and challenges where you build those stats and traits are

369
00:23:08,315 --> 00:23:13,676
largely randomized every time. So if you end up in the wrong encounters, you might be going stag.

370
00:23:14,536 --> 00:23:19,457
So that's one approach to the chemistry casino. The other is to fake randomization,

371
00:23:19,637 --> 00:23:21,118
a rigged casino, if you will.

372
00:23:21,631 --> 00:23:23,673
And this is where narrative really comes in.

373
00:23:24,153 --> 00:23:26,495
Because even if the player can just

374
00:23:26,535 --> 00:23:28,816
keep picking the right option and lock

375
00:23:28,856 --> 00:23:31,818
in a guaranteed romance, the narrative and other systems

376
00:23:31,858 --> 00:23:34,000
can make the relationship feel like luck.

377
00:23:34,520 --> 00:23:37,082
And yes, some people will filter it out and post a walkthrough.

378
00:23:37,142 --> 00:23:39,884
But you can ensure that those that go in blind still

379
00:23:39,944 --> 00:23:41,566
experience that feeling of gambling

380
00:23:41,606 --> 00:23:42,987
with their heart or loins.

381
00:23:43,707 --> 00:23:44,428
So how do you do that?

382
00:23:45,348 --> 00:23:47,990
Well, one of the easiest things to do is to hide everything.

383
00:23:48,170 --> 00:23:48,971
More specifically.

384
00:23:49,357 --> 00:23:55,519
Hide immediate feedback for romance actions. Don't indicate the right choices of what the NPCs think

385
00:23:55,699 --> 00:24:01,441
or like or think. Keep players in the dark the way real people are in the dark when they first

386
00:24:01,461 --> 00:24:07,063
start dating someone. Let them guess, let them stumble, let them experiment. The uncertainty

387
00:24:07,103 --> 00:24:12,605
drives tension and that tension is what you can tap into to power your romantic and sexual tension.

388
00:24:13,365 --> 00:24:13,525
Now

389
00:24:14,028 --> 00:24:18,010
The most obvious way to hide things, obviously, is the UI, making sure that there's no hearts,

390
00:24:18,270 --> 00:24:24,973
no pop-ups, no, you know, anything like that. But there is also feedback like that to hide

391
00:24:25,053 --> 00:24:30,536
and avoid in writing. In many romances, dialogue gives explicitly clear feedback whether the

392
00:24:30,576 --> 00:24:35,978
player's romantic interest is reciprocated or not. But what if your player flirted and instead

393
00:24:35,998 --> 00:24:40,620
of that, the NPC just raised an eyebrow, smiled a little bit, and changed the subject?

394
00:24:41,558 --> 00:24:44,081
cue your players going, oh my God, what does it mean?

395
00:24:44,761 --> 00:24:47,964
Which, you know, is kind of like real dating feels sometimes.

396
00:24:49,165 --> 00:24:51,006
So where format and scope allow,

397
00:24:51,206 --> 00:24:52,787
lean on things like body language

398
00:24:52,908 --> 00:24:54,609
that can be ambiguous and subtle.

399
00:24:55,630 --> 00:24:58,692
Other ways to make non-random romance systems feel random,

400
00:24:58,952 --> 00:25:02,015
there's the always the old, will they, won't they dynamic,

401
00:25:02,195 --> 00:25:04,537
but writing it in a way that makes they won't

402
00:25:04,917 --> 00:25:07,159
feel like equally likely outcome.

403
00:25:07,920 --> 00:25:12,088
you could try approaching it like a sexy romantic whodunit, only in this case the

404
00:25:12,128 --> 00:25:16,316
mystery isn't the identity of the killer, but the nature of the feelings involved.

405
00:25:16,999 --> 00:25:19,060
and write the eventual connection not as inevitable,

406
00:25:19,240 --> 00:25:22,981
even if it secretly is, but as a lucky win or a little miracle.

407
00:25:23,421 --> 00:25:26,142
And that can mean themes of motifs of happy chance

408
00:25:26,462 --> 00:25:28,283
and sexy coincidence, or it could just

409
00:25:28,303 --> 00:25:30,424
mean writing to capture that feeling of jumping out

410
00:25:30,444 --> 00:25:33,044
of a plane and finding out that, yes, oh my god,

411
00:25:33,084 --> 00:25:34,945
your parachute does, in fact, work.

412
00:25:35,425 --> 00:25:39,286
In other words, taking a chance, making the leap of faith,

413
00:25:39,867 --> 00:25:41,267
and it all working out in the end.

414
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:46,601
Remember, love and lust can sometimes be uncertain and confusing and possibly even terrifying,

415
00:25:47,102 --> 00:25:49,242
but that makes the successes all the sweeter.

416
00:25:50,482 --> 00:25:54,463
To see this in action, I highly recommend checking out the visual novel First Bite,

417
00:25:54,523 --> 00:25:59,285
because it's a great example of random-feeling narrative hiding a non-random chemistry card

418
00:25:59,305 --> 00:25:59,585
tower.

